{"type":"text","timestamp":1781083046507,"sessionID":"ses_14f2f6605ffeEk11ACiTpW64NC","part":{"id":"prt_eb0d26688001T1is8ZkyIGWzLj","messageID":"msg_eb0d25d22001mIj6e2gbt6Xq7J","sessionID":"ses_14f2f6605ffeEk11ACiTpW64NC","type":"text","text":"There's only `test.sh` in /tests at task root (the find restores exec on /tests after upload merge). It's a defensive no-op since no other .sh files exist there — but it costs nothing. Marginal.\n\nThere's a structural issue: there is **NO `environment/tests/`** directory. The Harbor convention says: \"All other test assets (scoring scripts, reference files, data, etc.) must live in `environment/tests/`\". Here `compute_reward.py` and `run_all.py` live in `tests/` at task root alongside `test.sh`. They are uploaded together to /tests via the docker compose cp merge at verify time.\n\nBut wait — does the Dockerfile build_tests.py also create test definitions baked into /tests? Yes: it generates fixtures, test JSON, and the Dockerfile bakes them into /tests. So /tests is built at image-build time AND merged again at verify time with these scripts. That actually works correctly, though convention-wise compute_reward.py and run_all.py should be in `environment/tests/`.\n\nActually — re-read the Harbor docs: tests/ at task root should contain ONLY test.sh. But compute_reward.py and run_all.py are also Harbor-internal scripts the verifier needs. The convention says they should be in environment/tests/. This is a minor convention violation that bloats the repo's tests/ dir.","time":{"start":1781083039368,"end":1781083046500}}}
