{"type":"text","timestamp":1781083057355,"sessionID":"ses_14f2f6605ffeEk11ACiTpW64NC","part":{"id":"prt_eb0d2932a001sa4tLzu3ckDpyw","messageID":"msg_eb0d28914001C2tW40tO5TlM2J","sessionID":"ses_14f2f6605ffeEk11ACiTpW64NC","type":"text","text":"Good. test.sh correctly avoids it.\n\nLet me look at `find /tests -mindepth 1 -path /tests/fixtures -prune -o -exec chmod go-rwx {} +` in Dockerfile — but `chmod 700 /tests` already locks /tests at top level. The recursive go-rwx strip ensures that if Harbor's upload resets the top dir back to 0755, the inner files are still go-readable=0. Then test.sh re-chmod 700 the top dir. This is sensible defense-in-depth.\n\nNow let me write the cleanliness report:\n\nSummary:\n- **dockerfile_quality**: WARN — `bc` is unused (verifier was rewritten to Python); `build-essential` + `gcc` + `g++` + `make` are redundant since `build-essential` includes them all.\n- **solution_clean**: PASS — only solve.sh; legitimate use of `set -euo pipefail`.\n- **testsh_quality**: PASS (minor) — every section serves a clear purpose for this complex task; some env unset list is mildly defensive but cheap.\n- **git_hygiene**: PASS — no >30MB files.\n- **workspace_clean**: PASS — workspace has only an examples/README.md placeholder explaining what gets generated at build time.","time":{"start":1781083050794,"end":1781083057346}}}
